<DOC><DOCNO> AP880524-0120 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 1127EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Sudan-Terrorism     05-24 0295</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Sudan-Terrorism,0305</SECOND><HEAD>Sudan Arrests 2 More In Terrorist Attacks, Abu Nidal ConnectionAlleged</HEAD><BYLINE>By SALAH ZARROUG</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Police have arrested two more members ofa gang that killed seven people and wounded 21 in two terroristattacks, a government spokesman said today.   Security sources, speaking anonymously under government rules,said all five suspects now in custody carry Lebanese passports andclaim to be Palestinians affiliated with terrorist leader Abu Nidal.   The suspects said they were retaliating for the April killing inTunisia of the Palestine Liberation Organization's militarycommander, Khalil Wazir, the sources reported. Palestinian groupsand others said Wazir's assassination was carried out Israelicommandos.   However, Sudan's prime minister had earlier ruled outPalestinian involvement in the May 15 attacks on the Sudan Club andHotel Acropol in Khartoum.   Information Minister Abdallah Mohammed Ahmed, the government'sofficial spokesman, said the suspects had confessed their roles inlast week's attacks. The final two suspects in the attacks werearrested Monday.   Gen. Ibrahim Ahmed Abdel-Karim, Khartoum's inspector of police,said last week the first three suspects said in their confessionsthat the attacks were directed ``against American and Britishinterests'' in the northeast African nation.   All the deaths, mostly of foreigners, occurred at the HotelAcropol, where two bombs went off outside the dining room as guestssat down for Sunday dinner. Shortly afterward, men opened fire withsubmachine guns at the front gate of the Sudan Club, reserved forBritish and Commonwealth nationals.   In a nationwide broadcast Friday, Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi,said, ``I rule out (any) relationship between the operation and aPalestinian national group.'' He suggested the attackers could havebeen hired by Israel to plant ``the seeds of doubt between Sudanand the Palestinian struggle.''</TEXT></DOC>